<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Somalia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demonstration Against Cargo Taxes Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA1802211194 (Clandestine) Radio Mogadishu Voice of the 
Great Somali People in Somali 1700 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1802211194 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Radio Mogadishu Voice of the 
Great Somali People </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Somali </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Reports from the main Mogadishu port say a 
disturbance took place at the port following an attempt by 
UNOSOM and its surrogates to impose taxes on cargo goods. The 
confrontation occurred yesterday between Mogadishu Somali 
citizens and UNOSOM mercenaries based at the port. 
  A reporter from Radio Mogadishu Voice of the Great Somali 
People, who witnessed the event, said the people were enraged by 
this foreign provocation. He said the people barricaded all the 
roads leading to the port with burning tires and carried 
placards with slogans expressing their indignation and 
opposition to the so-called taxes imposed on cargo goods at the 
port. Asked by our reporter about the taxation, one of the 
transport owners at the port said UNOSOM was not the country's 
central government and therefore had no right to levy taxes at 
Mogadishu Port, adding that they would prefer to die rather than 
pay taxes to UNOSOM. 
  Our reporter also said he had met some Mogadishu Port 
Corporation Officials, (MPOC), an agency appointed by UNOSOM to 
supervise the port's operations and which is composed of whites 
and pseudo- Somalis. The officials told our reporter that what 
UNOSOM had imposed on the Mogadishu Port was not taxes but a 
GATT tariff. They preferred the GATT tariff to tax, believing 
that Somalis would not interpret this as tax. 
  Whatever you call it -- tax, taxation, tariff, GATT, duty, 
levy and others -- basically they are all the same. The Somali 
people will not allow the invading foreigners to impose any 
types of taxes on them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-25476 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr035_b_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-035 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Somalia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denounces Abduction of 21 UK Experts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2002152994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1318 GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2002152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 20 Feb (MENA)--'Abdallah al-Tahir, foreign 
relations official of the United Somali Party, has denounced the 
detention of UK experts in any part of Somalia. 
  In an exclusive statement to MENA, al-Tahir said that the 
holding of 21 experts as hostages reflects the power struggle 
between the militias of Abdirahman Ali, former President of 
northern Somalia, and Mohamed Ibrahim Egal, current president of 
the so-called northern Somalia. 
  Al-Tahir, who is on a visit to Cairo, said that the 
abduction 
is also a result of the widespread frustration in Burco and 
Hargeysa, the two provinces that support secession. The three 
other provinces are opposed to secession, he stated. 
  The Somali official expressed his hope that the United 
Kingdom would withhold its support to the secession following 
this incident and instead help the Somalis emerge united, not 
divided, from the current crisis. 
  Al-Tahir said that he briefed Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa and 
Arab League Secretary General Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid on the 
current developments in the country. Egypt, he added, promised 
to hold consultations with foreign countries and utilize its 
friendship with these countries in helping the Somalis face the 
current crisis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

