<H3> <TI>   Denies Making Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2002052094 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in English 1800 
GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2002052094 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] IFP [Inkatha Freedom Party] leader Mangosuthu 
Buthelezi has denied reports which quoted him as saying he would 
not take part in the April election even if his demands were met 
by the government and the ANC [African National Congress]. In a 
telephone interview from Ulundi, Dr. Buthelezi accused the media 
of malicious and irresponsible reporting: 
  [Buthelezi] I would like to say that that is absolutely 
false. I take this as part and parcel of the propaganda that is 
being mounted by certain sections of the media against me, 
against the IFP, and against the Freedom Alliance, because I 
would be mad to talk like that. Because, after all, even today 
there was a meeting between my colleagues and members of the 
government. They were seeking ways of trying to find a way 
which would make us participate if our concerns, as expressed in 
the document of the 19th of December which we gave to both the 
ANC and the government, were met. All I said when one of the 
journalists was putting the question is that in fact it seems to 
me that the government and ANC were deliberately stringing us 
along until we were left without any time to campaign. 
  Dr. Buthelezi was allegedly misquoted after he spoke to 
local 
and foreign journalists at Johannesburg's Jan Smuts Airport 
following a meeting with Swedish Foreign Minister Margaretha af 
Ugglas. 

</TEXT>

