<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zulu King Addresses Chiefs on Independent State </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1902162094 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1556 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1902162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by L. Roderick] </F>
  [Text] Piet Retief, South-Eastern Transvaal, Feb 19 SAPA -- 
Zulu monarch, King Goodwill Zwelithini, says he hopes all people 
in Natal/kwaZulu will accept him as their king. Speaking to a 
gathering of Zulus near Piet Retief on Saturday [19 February], 
he said he stood firm on his call for an independent Zulu 
monarchy. 
  "I want to give my assurance to all the people of 
kwaZulu/Natal that all your needs will be met under a Zulu 
monarchy," he said, promising to uphold democratic and 
pluralistic values. 
  "This independent state would offer full protection to all 
its people as individuals and members of social and cultural 
formations," he said. 
  The king, at a meeting with State President F W de Klerk 
last 
week announced his plans for secession from South Africa, 
rejecting participation in the country's first non-racial 
election in April. Explaining his move on Saturday, he said 
South Africa's interim constitution was a "threat" to the status 
and institutions of the Zulu kingdom. "The constitution has 
reduced you to playing a minimal tribal and administrative role 
in the running of your communities," he told the gathering of 
tribal leaders and chiefs. 
  He raised the concern that the constitution did not include 
a 
provision which would "ensure that a new government will not 
take the land the monarchy has held in trust for the Zulu 
people". 
  He said his claim for an independent Zulu state was based on 
historical precedent and had been his intention prior to kwaZulu 
Chief Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi's "warning" of a deadlock on 
the question of federalism in constitution negotiations. 
  He called on the tribal chiefs and leaders to "stand 
together" if they were to survive the threats and challenges he 
claimed were being faced by the zulu people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

