<H3> <TI>   Bophuthatswana, ANC Delegations End `Positive' Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1802155494 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 1500 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1802155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bophuthatswana Government and ANC [African National 
Congress] negotiating delegations may meet again this weekend, 
following a positive round of exploratory talks in 
Bophuthatswana today. The head of the Bophuthatswana 
delegation, Mr. Ephraim Keikelane, said after a meeting in the 
Pilanesberg Game Reserve that they had suggested that 
Bophuthatswana should have a confederal relationship with South 
Africa. Mr. Popo Molefe of the ANC said they have spelled out 
the ANC's latest constitutional proposals in detail. He said 
both sides would report back to their principals, and a second 
round of talks was imminent, possibly before the negotiating 
council met on Monday [21 February]. 

