<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demands Listed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2102204794 Luanda TPA Television Network in Portuguese 
1930 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2102204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda TPA Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone report by correspondent Joao Ligio in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] The proceedings at the Lusaka peace talks this week 
is seen as one of the most difficult stages in the second round 
of the talks. For the first time, National Union for the Total 
Independence of Angola [UNITA] has complied with its promise to 
present its response to the first proposal, which sought to 
narrow differences concerning the specific principles that will 
govern the national reconciliation process. In practice, it 
turned a blind eye to the protocols and understandings that have 
already been reached. 
  UNITA wants three of the government's six key ministries; it 
wants provincial governments to have autonomous powers and their 
own police forces; it wants participation in all strategic 
companies, including the National Angolan Fuel Company, 
Sonangol, and the Angola National Diamond Enterprise, Endiama, 
which are viewed as preferred targets. It wants public 
competition for a new symbol of the Republic and a new national 
anthem. It wants immunity for its men and diplomatic passports, 
and it wants its property returned. 
  The government team to the talks was called this afternoon 
to 
respond to UNITA's position. It admitted that it might make 
some concessions, but it described the document as contradicting 
the principles that have already been signed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

