<H3> <TI>   Opposition Takes 2-Seat Lead </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2102213094 Paris AFP in English 2118 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2102213094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lome, Feb 21 (AFP) -- Togo's pro-democracy 
opposition took a two-seat lead over parties backing President 
Gnassingbe Eyadema in the country's first multi-party elections, 
according to partial official results from a second round of 
polling released late Monday [21 February]. 
  The National Election Commission said opposition parties had 
secured 17 of the 24 seats available in the second round, while 
the pro-Eyadema Togolese People's Rally had won two, and 
transitional Premier Joseph Koffigoh one. The results from four 
remaining seats were not released. 
  The results meant that after two rounds of voting, 
pro-opposition parties had won 39 seats, compared to 37 for 
pro-Eyadema parties, holding out the prospect of an end to the 
monopoly on power exercised by Eyadema since 1967. 

</TEXT>

