<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Chad </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government-CSNPD Hold Peace Talks in Bangui </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2302151594 Bangui Radiodiffusion-Television Centrafricaine 
Radio in French 1800 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB2302151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangui Radiodiffusion-Television Centrafricaine 
Radio </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The delegations of the Ndjamena Government and 
the National Awakening Committee for Peace and Democracy [CSNPD] 
started peace talks in Bangui this morning under the auspices of 
the Central African Republic [CAR]. The CAR agreed to assume 
this historic responsibility of peace broker at the request of 
Chadian President Idriss Deby. The talks are designed to 
restore peace in southern Chad. 
  To demonstrate the CAR Government's willingness to play its 
mediating role, Prime Minister Jean-Luc Mandaba made a point of 
personally presiding over the opening ceremony which was 
attended by the leaders of the two delegations and members of 
the president's office as well as cabinet members, officials 
from the prime minister's office, the judiciary, the National 
Assembly, and representatives of the CAR political parties. 
Speaking on this occasion, the prime minister stated that the 
time had come to silence arms and give priority to dialogue. He 
called for the setting up of a follow-up committee to monitor 
the implementation of any accords that will be reached during 
the roundtable talks. He pointed out that the CAR and the 
Chadian people were interested in seeing these negotiations 
yield positive results. 
  [Begin Mandaba recording] It is with much hope that, at your 
request, we have agreed to play the noble task of mediator 
between the government of President Deby and the delegation of 
the political-cum-military opposition movement based in southern 
Chad. The choice of the CAR was not made by chance since we 
share a long common border. We have always been a natural safe 
haven for our Chadian brothers. Our exchanges and relations in 
all sectors have been cordial and frank and our two countries 
have always resorted to dialogue in settling any border dispute 
in compliance with the OAU and UN principles and ideals. 
Chadian and CAR nationals have always worked hand in hand in 
their efforts to safeguard their common interests. [passage 
omitted] We hope that the two delegations did not come 
empty-handed and will not leave here empty-handed. That is why 
we strongly appeal to them to ensure that 1994 will be the year 
of peace, an indispensable factor for the much needed economic 
and political development of Chad. [passage omitted] [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

