<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Uganda </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rebels Attack Health Facility in North </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2602212394 Paris AFP in English 0426 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2602212394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kampala, Feb 25 (AFP) -- Rebels calling themselves 
members of the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) overrun a dispensary 
on the Gulu-Kitgum road in northern Uganda on Friday [25 
February] and looted all the medical supplies, Ugandan police 
said here on Friday. 
  "We have heard of it but we do not have details", a police 
spokesman told AFP on telephone. 
  Police said that the rebels, estimated at 20, attacked the 
dispensary, taking patients and medical staff unaware, fired in 
the air to disperse patients and medical personnel and then 
looted all drugs available. 
  The attack was the latest on civilian targets by the rebels, 
who have defied an ultimatum by President Yoweri Museveni on 
February 13 to surrender. 
  On the day the ultimatum was supposed to expire -- February 
20 -- the rebels led by Joseph Kony, a man in his late twenties, 
attacked an army unit at Tegot-Pawel, 50 kilometers (30 miles) 
north of Gulu town, during which four army soldiers and 14 
rebels were reported killed. 
  On Monday the rebels ambushed a police vehicle near Ayugi 
river, 11 kms (seven miles) along the Atiak-Moyo road in 
northwest Uganda, killing 11 people, including two soldiers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

