<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mali </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tuareg Leader Killed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2802100794 Bamako Radiodiffusion-Television du Mali Radio 
in French 0700 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB2802100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bamako Radiodiffusion-Television du Mali Radio 
in French 0700 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We learned yesterday that Colonel Saloum Bilal, a 
Popular Movement of the Azaouad military leader, died on 25 
February following an attack by armed bandits in an area 100 km 
from Gao. Alpha Mengar, our permanent correspondent in Poure, 
has the details. 
  [Mengar] Rumors on the colonel's death spread all over Gao. 
While people were having tea in front of shops after prayers, 
the story on everyone's lips was that Col. Bilal had been 
attacked and that he was dead. 
  It must be said that Col. Bilal is, above all, seen as one 
of 
the architects of the peace process which was embarked upon 
following the signing of the National Pact on 11 April 1992. He 
had survived several ambushes in the past. One person died in 
this recent attack and one was seriously wounded. A third was 
abducted by the attackers, and a fourth escaped. 
  A reliable source close to the cease-fire monitoring 
committee stated: All we can say is that Bilal died following 
an attack by an unidentified number of armed bandits in a 
vehicle. Following the signing of the National Pact, Saloum 
Bilal married Bintu Shadeya, first runner-up in the Sike-Askia 
beauty competition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

