<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Togo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Not To Interfere in Election Disputes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2602224794 Lome Radio Lome in French 2200 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2602224794 </F>
<F P=104>  Lome Radio Lome </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [`Clarification' issued by the Lome government on the </F>
results of the elections; date not given] 
  [Text] Let us begin this newscast with a clarification from 
the government. The National Electoral Commission [CEN] has 
announced the partial results for the 19 constituencies where 
the 20 February elections took place. However, it was of the 
view that it was not in a position to announce the results for 
the five remaining constituencies, where serious incidents 
disrupted the smooth running of the electoral exercise. The CEN 
has, therefore, submitted the dossier to the Supreme Court. 
  The government has no intention of interfering in the 
settlement of the election disputes. It hopes that the 
competent organs, which are provided by the Constitution and the 
Electoral Law to settle electoral disputes, will be able to make 
their decisions with full sovereignty -- and without any 
pressure. It will do everything in its power to facilitate the 
establishment of the institutions of the Fourth Republic with 
peace and security for all. 
  Finally, the government hopes that everyone will respect the 
Constitution and the Electoral Law, as is the tradition in each 
of the countries serving on the Internatonal Follow Up Committee. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-25735 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr039_e_94007" </HT>


