<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Points of Discussion Described </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2702221494 Lisbon Radio Renascenca in Portuguese to Europe 
2100 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2702221494 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon Radio Renascenca </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Angolan Government and UNITA [National Union for the 
Total Independence of Angola] delegations at the Lusaka peace 
talks met this evening to try and overcome the differences 
preventing an agreement on the specific principles for national 
reconciliation. 
  A source at the talks said that the meeting is being held as 
a response to a request by the observers who hope that one 
week-old differences will be overcome and hope that the two 
sides will approve specific principles for national 
reconciliation tomorrow. One of the points of disagreement that 
is being discussed at the meeting relates to UNITA's radio 
station the Voice of the Resistance of the Black Cockerel, also 
known as VORGAN. According to Angolan legislation, political 
parties can own publications but cannot own radio stations. 
Meanwhile, UNITA considers VORGAN an exception because it 
already existed before the legislation was approved. 
  Another point of disagreement relates to the country's 
administrative decentralization, which the government says is 
already being implemented. Meanwhile, UNITA wants provincial 
government to have its own power, at several levels, as well as 
its own budgetary capacities. Moreover, UNITA wants the 
principle relating to holding provincial and locals elections to 
be defined in Lusaka, following a transitional period. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

