<H3> <TI>   Ghana's Rawlings Stops Over in Luanda </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2802075094 Luanda TPA Television Network in Portuguese 
1930 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2802075094 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda TPA Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The new winds of democracy blowing over our 
continent represent a historic opportunity. That was said by 
Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings when he stopped over in Luanda 
this morning on his way to Namibia. He was welcomed by National 
Assembly Chairman Franca van Dunem, government members, and 
officials of the Ghanaian Embassy in Angola. 
  [Begin Rawlings recording, in English fading into Portuguese 
translation] I realize the Angolan war has been provoked by the 
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola [UNITA]. 
The winds of democracy blowing over our continent represent a 
historic opportunity not only to individual countries, but to 
all of them. We ought to do away with ethnic differences because 
they create problems, not to the better off, but to the 
underprivileged. I think it would be good if we could take this 
magnificent opportunity to establish democracy in Africa. We 
have no other option. This is our continent and we ought to 
work together. [end recording] 
  President Rawlings then left for Namibia. 

</TEXT>

