<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Zimbabwe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ethiopia Formally Requests Mengistu Extradition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2602211594 Paris AFP in English 1359 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2602211594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Harare, Feb 26 (AFP) -- Ethiopia has formally asked 
Zimbabwe to extradite former dictator, Mengistu Haile Mariam, so 
he can be tried for crimes committed during his 17-year reign. 
  Ethiopian ambassador to Zimbabwe, Fantahum Michael, told AFP 
Saturday [26 February] that he personally presented the request 
to Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Nathan Shamuyarira on Wednesday. 
  He said Shamuyarira told him he would present the request to 
the cabinet and a response could be expected at a later date. 
  The Zimbabwean authorities have not yet responded publicly 
to 
the request. 
  Mengistu fled to Zimbabwe just before a 1991 uprising in his 
country and was granted political asylum by President Robert 
Mugabe, a former ally, in May 1991. 
  Early this month, Mengistu breached one of his conditions of 
asylum, and broke years of silence over his home country saying 
Ethiopia was in a "disgusting" state and that he had plans to 
rescue it. 
  Michael, however said the extradition request was not 
sparked 
off by Mengistu's recent outburst. 
  He said it was a coincidence as preparations had already 
been 
underway to ask for his extradition. 
  The request was finalised in Addis Ababa on February 15 and 
brought to Harare this week by a team of European lawyers 
helping the government of Meles Zenawi investigate Mengistu's 
human rights violations together with some members of the office 
of the special prosecutor of Ethiopia. 
  The request documents detail Mengistu's abuse of human 
rights, which included the massacre of at least 100,000 
Ethiopians. 
  Analysts say it is likely to take months before Zimbabwe 
answers to the request as it will take legal experts from both 
countries, as well as international agencies to meet and examine 
the various points of international law under which the 
extradition and trial should take place. 
  The DAILY GAZETTE newspaper said Saturday that the Ethiopian 
Government was also seeking the extradition of Mengistu's aides, 
24 of whom were in Kenya, 14 in the United States, six in Europe 
and several others in other African nations. 
  Three of the wanted aides are reportedly holed up in the 
Italian Embassy in Addis Ababa and many others are already in 
Ethiopian Government custody. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-25756 </DOCNO>
