<H3> <TI>   OAU's Salim Urges IFP To Participate in Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2502193194 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in English 1600 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2502193194 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Organization of African Unity has added its 
voice to those urging the IFP [Inkatha Freedom Party] to take 
part in the election. OAU Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim 
met IFP leader Dr. Mangosuthu Buthelezi in Ulundi today. 
  [Begin recording] [Correspondent Gary Alfonso] The OAU 
leader's visit to Ulundi for talks with the IFP and the kwaZulu 
government was the first by a leader of this organization. Both 
Dr. Ahmed Salim and Buthelezi made one thing clear: They had 
different views and perspectives of the transition process and 
especially the elections. 
  [Salim] I believe in this because of these discussions that 
it will be vital in the interest of South Africa that everything 
be done to ensure an all inclusive election where the 
participation of all the political forces in the country, and 
certainly the participation of Inkatha Freedom Party also is 
possible. 
  [Buthelezi] We definitely are doing everything worthwhile 
because we are very keen to participate in the elections, and 
therefore even now at this last moment -- even today -- our 
members of parliament I think, are talking to a select committee 
of Parliament about some of the amendments which were proposed 
by the IFP and the Freedom Alliance. 
  [Alfonso] Both leaders also confirmed that international 
mediation, especially by the OAU, was of critical importance. 
Dr. Buthelezi said free political activity had become almost 
impossible in most parts of Natal. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

