<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mandela Praises Defense Forces' Requirements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2502173994 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1436 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2502173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by P Claasen] </F>
  [Text] Kimberley Feb 25 SAPA -- The African National 
Congress [ANC] did not want to lower the high standards of the 
South African Defence Force [SADF], ANC leader Nelson Mandela 
said on Friday [25 February]. He was addressing 10,000 people 
who attended a peoples' forum to raise issues with the 
leadership at the Galeshewe Stadium in Kimberley. 
  A questioner asked how matriculation could remain a 
qualification for membership of the ANC's armed wing Umkhonto we 
Sizwe (MK) [Spear of the Nation] if the future government was to 
provide only 10 years of free education. 
  Mr Mandela said MK members must at least have a 
matriculation 
certificate. "The SADF, with which we are now uniting and which 
has had an opportunity for education, is very well qualified. 
Officers require certain academic qualifications and many of 
them are highly educated." 
  This was evident at a recent meeting with the General Staff 
of the SADF at which he could see from the way they presented 
their arguments that they were well educated. "We do not want 
to bring down the standards of the army. We want to keep them 
as high as they are," he said. "Even in the reorganisation we 
will not get the qualifications we want; we must have at least 
matric," he said. The 10 years of free education was a first 
target and a future government would hope to increase it in 
stages. 

</TEXT>

